Artificial Intelligence Adoption and Operational Efficiency: Evidence from UK FTSE 350 Financial Institutions 
This dissertation examines whether artificial intelligence (AI) adoption improves the operational efficiency of UK-listed financial institutions. The topic is timely for three reasons. First, financial firms are among the most intensive users of data, automation and predictive analytics. Second, AI adoption has accelerated since 2019, but the benefits may differ substantially across large incumbents and mid-cap firms because of scale, regulatory capacity and legacy systems. Third, existing discussion often assumes that AI improves efficiency, yet there is still limited firm-level evidence for UK listed financial institutions using consistent panel methods and comparable disclosure-based measures. The proposed study therefore asks: does a higher level of AI adoption lead to better operational efficiency among firms in the FTSE 350 financial sector? A related sub-question is whether the effect is stronger for FTSE 100 firms than for FTSE 250 firms. 
The study is motivated by theories of technological adoption, resource-based advantage and organisational efficiency. From a resource-based perspective, firms with stronger data infrastructure, managerial capabilities and capital resources should be better placed to convert AI investment into productivity gains. At the same time, implementation costs, adjustment frictions and compliance obligations may delay the realisation of those gains, especially in regulated sectors such as banking and insurance. This implies that the relationship between AI adoption and performance is unlikely to be immediate or uniform. The dissertation contributes by testing whether AI-related disclosure intensity predicts subsequent improvements in operational efficiency, while allowing for heterogeneity across firm size and financial sub-sectors. 
The sample will include all financial firms in the FTSE 350, combining firms from the FTSE 100 and FTSE 250 that are classified as financials. The intended period is 2019Q1 to 2025Q4, giving a quarterly panel with sufficient variation across firms and time. The main dependent variable will be the cost-to-income ratio, which is widely used as a proxy for operational efficiency in financial services. Where available, robustness checks will also consider complementary indicators such as return on assets, revenue per employee or non-interest expense ratios, depending on sub-sector comparability. The key independent variable will be an AI adoption score derived from textual analysis of company disclosures using Bloomberg Document Search. Specifically, quarterly trading updates, earnings transcripts and annual reports will be searched for AI-related terms such as artificial intelligence, machine learning, generative AI, natural language processing, neural networks, robotic process automation and related expressions. To reduce measurement error, raw keyword counts will be normalised by document length and lagged by one quarter in the baseline model. 
The empirical strategy will use panel data regression with firm fixed effects and time fixed effects. This approach controls for unobserved, time-invariant firm characteristics and common macroeconomic shocks. The baseline model will estimate whether AI adoption at time t-1 is associated with operational efficiency at time t. Additional specifications will test differences between FTSE 100 and FTSE 250 firms, and between banks, insurers, asset managers and other financial services firms. Control variables are expected to include firm size, leverage, capital adequacy or solvency measures where relevant, revenue growth, loan-loss provisions for banks, and macroeconomic variables such as GDP growth, inflation and policy rates. Standard errors will be clustered at the firm level. Robustness checks may include alternative keyword dictionaries, annual rather than quarterly aggregation, and the exclusion of outlier observations. 
The project is feasible within the dissertation timeframe because the core data sources are accessible through Bloomberg and company filings. The work plan is as follows. In late April and early May, I will finalise the literature review, define the AI keyword dictionary and pilot the Bloomberg search strategy on a small set of firms. In May and June, I will construct the FTSE 350 financial sample and download quarterly accounting and disclosure data. In June and July, I will clean the dataset, estimate the baseline and robustness models, and interpret the findings. In July and early August, I will complete the empirical chapters, conclusion and final editing before submission. Overall, the dissertation aims to provide a focused and empirically testable assessment of whether AI adoption is already translating into measurable efficiency gains in UK financial institutions, and whether those gains are concentrated among larger firms with greater technological and organisational capacity.
 
