Theoretical Framework and Background Information This research is grounded in the Resource-Based View (RBV) of the firm and Information Processing Theory. Under RBV, AI capabilities are viewed as strategic, intangible resources that, when integrated effectively, can provide a sustained competitive advantage through cost leadership. Previous literature highlights conflicting evidence regarding immediate financial returns on IT investments, suggesting a time lag between adoption and realized efficiency. This study will outline a framework based on existing literature to analyze how AI adoption acts as an operational lever to reduce relative costs over time.
Design and Methods The study adopts a quantitative empirical design, specifying all variables and anticipated relationships. The sample encompasses all financial firms within the FTSE 350 Financials Index (approximately 50 firms). To ensure a robust dataset with sufficient degrees of freedom for econometric testing, the study utilizes quarterly data spanning from 2019 to 2025, yielding approximately 1,000 observations.
The independent variable, AI adoption, will be quantified using textual analytics. Using the Bloomberg Document Search (DS) function, the frequency of specific AI-related keywords (e.g., "Machine Learning", "Neural Networks", "Robotic Process Automation", "Natural Language Processing", "AI") will be measured within companies' quarterly trading updates and annual filings. The dependent variable, acting as the primary proxy for operational efficiency, is the Cost-to-Income Ratio (CIR). To isolate the effect of AI, the study incorporates control variables including firm size (Ln Total Assets), Leverage, Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR), alongside macroeconomic indicators such as GDP and inflation rates. All data will be collected from secondary statistical sources and corporate reports.
